  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Malaria is still endemic in the interior of French Guiana. mixed infections by 2 or more
      different malaria parasites lead to complex and potentially harmfull therapeutic problems.
      The aim of the study was to look at malaria smears between 2000 and 2008 and determine using
      PCR the frequency of mixed infections, and their distribution in the terrtory of French
      Guiana. Overall 10.75% of 400 smears showed mixed infection with P. falciparum and P. vivax.
      The Maroni river where Duffy negative populations live was largely devoid of vivax
      infections. These results suggest that mixed infections are frequent in french guiana except
      on the Maroni river which leads to practical implications for clinicians facing a patient
      with clinical malaria.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
